name: Rory Doyle
bio: Working + traveling photographer/drone pilot in Mississippi, American South + beyond. Based in Cleveland, MS 🍕@lenapizzabagels co-founder + @marisoldo

social_posts.post_text: Recent work for @washingtonpost, and in this case, a really hard story to accept. Nationwide, the homicide rate has reached record levels in recent years. Mariyah Lacy was 4 when she buried her dad, Cornelius. A year later, Mariyah was shot in the back of her mother's truck. Both were victims of gun violence in Mississippi. Treasha Lacy graciously opened her home to us to explain the deep pain of losing both her son and granddaughter. Reporting by Sarah Fowler. Big thanks to editor @nataliajimenez.

My work on the front page of Neue Zürcher Zeitung (@NZZ) out of Switzerland. While Jackson, Mississippi's water crisis isn't currently the top international headline, the issue is just as significant now as it was back when I made these photos in October. Article by @dasigner2019 and big thanks to editor @dariovereb. Link in profile.

@CoulterFussell for the new issue of @GardenAndGun. It was a big honor to spend time at Coulter's colorful studio in Water Valley, MS. I've been inspired by Coulter's distinctive designs for a while — it was pretty awesome to photograph her in her element. Also, she might be part of the most artistic family ever! Big thanks to editor @maggiebrettkennedy

Work for @NPR about the lack of livestock veterinarians, a serious problem in rural America. Words by Scott Nueman:

One night last spring, Andy Berry, a livestock farmer in Mississippi, was working the phone. One of his cows was experiencing a life-threatening breech birth and his regular veterinarian, 40 minutes away, was unavailable.⁠
⁠
Berry spent two hours calling around for help, finally reaching another vet, who immediately made the one-hour drive to his farm in rural Jefferson Davis County.⁠
⁠
By the time she arrived, it was too late. "Ultimately, we ended up losing both the cow and the calf," Berry, 48, says. "Between the time it took to get to the farm and the complications of the labor, it was too much."⁠
⁠
Experiences similar to Berry's are becoming more common across the country. For decades, farmers have endured a shortage of rural veterinarians – the kind who specialize in care for animals like cows, pigs and sheep. But the problem is now at an all-time high – with 500 counties across 46 states reporting critical shortages this year, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture.⁠
⁠
- Additional photos from @michaelnoblejr. Big thanks to editors @catiedull and @grace.widyatmadja. Link in bio.

On rare occasions, travel leads you to places that truly feel like home away from home. I first learned about @atelierines_arts_suites on assignment for @fathomwaytogo in Naples, Italy over the summer. Marisol and I loved staying there, but really, we were amazed by the fact that this hotel is actually a living/breathing multi-generation art gallery, with an active studio, featuring the work of owners @vincenzo_oste_gioielli and Inès Sellami. We became pretty friends with the owners and stayed for a couple weeks earlier this month while Marisol took an advanced pizza course at the prestigious @pizzanapoletanaverace. If you plan to visit Naples, you must stay here! Read about it and check out my photos at the link in profile. Big thanks to @pavianyc + @jgerba 🇮🇹

@NyTimes coverage today of a tragic story out of small-town Eudora, Arkansas. Two homicides in the last 6 months, one on Christmas Eve, and now the mayor has instituted an 8 p.m. curfew for everyone. Some are questioning the constitutionality. Article by @lifestylesoftherickanddfamous. Thank you to editor @jennifermosbrucker. Link in bio.

I'm a little late announcing this due to a crazy schedule lately, but I'm incredibly honored to be part of a meaningful book from @NatGeo called "Inside the Curve: Stories from the Pandemic." Photographers and journalists around the world collaborated to document the challenges of the last three years, but also the hope that resulted from global efforts to combat it. My contribution is thanks to the big-hearted Tracy Harden, owner of Chuck's Dairy Bar in Rolling Fork, Mississippi. After years of historic flooding, a shrinking population, and then the pandemic, the rural lower Mississippi Delta knew they could always count on Chuck's to keep them fed. If you're interested in getting the book, check out the link in profile. Big thanks to @rstrec at @insidenatgeo.

It's hard to comprehend — to keep photographing the story of the Jackson, Mississippi water crisis. The suffering this is causing Jackson residents is unacceptable. For the @Guardian, I spent time with a grandmother caring for her eight grandchildren, a son with  sickle cell anemia, and a daughter who spends her days distributing drinking water to citizens across the city. Reporting by @ollyla and big thanks to editor @fletchinator. Link in profile.

New work today for @WSJ about the booming natural gas and oil industries in the U.S. The Biden administration has limited drilling on federal lands, but corporations have tapped the nation’s vast private shale reserves to drive production higher. I visited rural northwest Louisiana to see how both companies and private landowners are raking it in during the latest boom. Words by @benmorenne and big thanks to editor @allison_pasek. Link in bio.

My words are going to fall short, but here goes:

I'm so proud of this awe-inspiring woman, busting glass ceilings! After working in the restaurant industry for nearly 2 decades, @marisoldo is finally going to have her own brick and mortar. Today, over 2,700 pounds of made-in-Italy brick oven arrived on a massive pallet in downtown Cleveland, Mississippi. Her restaurant will be called Leña, which is Spanish for firewood, and a tribute to her humble upbringing in Mexico. @tasteoflena 

Marisol has worked in dough for years, but she rose to new levels this past year after 2 intensive Neapolitan pizza courses, along with a stage in Napoli. Handmade and heartfelt, she'll be offering brick oven pizza (following Italian traditions) and bagels.

We're both honored to bring this new option to Cleveland, and grateful for all the community support we've already received. We're both "outsiders" who've decided to put down roots here because of one reason — the people. Thank you for accepting us.

Please bear with us. We're a couple months away from opening, but we're moving as fast as we can. We can't wait to serve you and bring a few jobs into town. Angel Investors out there, please touch down 🙏 + 🍕+ 🥯

Honored to work with writer @moriahdb for this important @WashingtonPost article about a dire teacher shortage — a problem plaguing districts across the country, particularly ones that are rural and operating on limited funding. We visited the West Bolivar Consolidated School District here in the Delta. Kids are stuck taking classes via software programs on laptops or Zoom sessions where the teachers are at other schools. Many teachers are leading subjects they have no training in. Difficult to comprehend. Big thanks @markumpixs. Link in bio.

Hands down, @DomFlemons is one of the most talented and unique Grammy winners. His new record will be released in March by @smithsonianfolkways, and I'm incredibly honored to have photos featured throughout the album art, including the cover image. @sylviamarinamartinez created mesmerizing collages to bring the design to life, and I love how she incorporated the photos. The "Slow Dance With You" track is beautiful. Take a listen + order. Link in bio.
The ice is still wild down here in MS - on assignment — Como, Mississippi

Big Mike — Humphreys County, Mississippi

#TBT

As the war in Ukraine reached one year, @de_volkskrant featured stories of nine people around the world to show how the war has changed their lives. The paper sent me to Camden, Arkansas with writer @thomasrueb to document lifelong resident Danny Glaze. This rural town feels pretty low-key, but it's a major player in the American arms industry. Bombs, missiles, drones and the artillery systems that keep Ukraine afloat are being built in Camden factories — and for the first time in decades, there's a housing shortage in town. "I see those images and only think — those Russians are being killed with our weapons," said Glaze. Big thanks to editor @veroniquesmedts
My wife's new restaurant (@lenapizzabagels) is hiring part-time and full-time positions in historic downtown Cleveland, MS. Give her page a follow + see job descriptions. Grazie 🍕 🧡
L.C. "Buckshot" Smith, 94, the oldest active cop in the nation. Just imagine his stories...his life experiences. Photographed recently for @de_volkskrant — Camden, Arkansas
Devastation in Rolling Fork. Whatever support you can provide, please do. Photographed for @nytimes.
Jarvis, on his late mother’s steps. Jaden on his late grandmother’s steps. All that remains — Rolling Fork, MS

The news cycle shifts seemingly in seconds these days. Long-term support is needed in Rolling Fork, MS and other MS communities hit recently. @mstodaynews has a comprehensive list of ways to help. Link in bio.

Amidst the turbulence, I'm incredibly honored to share that my photo "First to Vote" won first place in the American Experience category of the 20th annual @smithsonianmagazine Photo Contest. Valerie Williams was first in line at her polling place, before sunrise, with her book and chair for the 2022 midterms in Atlanta, Georgia. There's a common narrative that people don't  care enough about voting — Ms. Williams proved otherwise!

This one for the @nytimes was a tough assignment — sex abuse, beatings and an untouchable Mississippi sheriff. As abuse allegations in a rural jail piled up, criminal inquiries dragged on or went nowhere. No one scrutinized how the sheriff ran his jail. Incredible reporting from @ilyssadaly @jmitchellnews. Big thanks to editor stephenreiss. Link in bio.

@talamieka Brice and her daughter, Love, in Duck Hill, MS today. Brice managed to get the Mississippi Department of Archives & History to install a historic marker for two Black lynching victims in Duck Hill, brutally murdered 86 years ago today.

Pretty stoked to publish a big photo essay in the @Guardian today about the 20th annual Juke Joint Festival in Clarksdale, MS. Even got to dust off my writing skills a little bit too. When it comes to the blues, there's nothing like Clarksdale! Link in bio.
Greg and gar, 4.23.23 — Greenville, Mississippi

Just published in @geomagazin, one of the most fascinating assignments I've had recently. In the middle of a wide open field in Arkansas, diamonds rise to the surface at Crater of Diamonds State Park. You pay to enter, but if you find a diamond, it's yours to keep. Writer @johannesmusial and I spoke to remarkable people out there — some chasing the American Dream, others looking for financial stability after facing life challenges. We put so much value on a tiny stone found in dirt...Big thanks to editor @larslindemann_geo. Link in bio, but there is a paywall.

Working on some long-form storytelling about fascinating bluesman Watermelon Slim, 74, from Clarksdale, Mississippi. If you aren't familiar with Slim, please look him up. He has remarkable and tragic life stories, is a Vietnam vet, and he's traveled the world with his guitar.

I'm honored to announce this work is supported by @fujifilmx_us through a flagship program with their stellar X-H2S camera (does amazing in low light). Working alongside videographer @meetmattwatson, we're utilizing the camera's built in Camera to Cloud system @frame_io from @adobe. I can send photos to editors directly from the camera. Technology is wild! Big thanks Fujifilm 🙏

New work today for @NBCNews about the lack of tornado shelters in the area. Rolling Fork is one of the many Mississippi communities without a public tornado safe room. As always, great reporting from @BraceyH. Big thanks @mattnighswander. Link in bio.
Rare portrait, me in Monument Valley on the Arizona/Utah border — photographed by reporter @thomasrueb

New work for @NYTimes about how climate change around the globe is drastically impacting rice production. I photographed in the Arkansas Delta, accompanied by photos from @chencocot in the Mekong Delta of Vietnam. Incredible reporting from @SominiSengupta. Big thanks to editor @mcmarbled. Link in bio.

Stating the obvious here, but opening a restaurant is no easy task. I'm incredibly proud of Chef @Marisoldo for working tirelessly each day to bring @LenaPizzaBagels to life. It's remarkable when you see that every pizza, every bagel, is shaped by her hands. Neither of us imagined owning our own restaurant — and it wouldn't be possible without Marisol's dedication, passion and brilliance. And thanks to the Cleveland and Mississippi Delta communities that have continued to support her. Eat local and come see us 🍕❤️🥯
Mr. Archie, at the Club Ebony reopening last night — Indianola, Mississippi
An unforgettable @susantedeschitrucks headliner performance at @bbkingmuseum's Club Ebony reopening concert in Indianola, Mississippi. A privilege to work this one.

New work for @de_volkskrant (Amsterdam) alongside writer @thomasrueb. We traveled to Navajo Nation, America's largest indigenous reservation, to meet some residents receiving power and water for the first time in history. About 30 percent of the 173,000 inhabitants still live without electricity, even more without drinking water.

location.city_name: Medgar and Myrlie Evers Home National Monument

social_posts.post_text: New work for @washingtonpost featuring Myrlie Evers-Williams on the 60th anniversary of the murder of Civil Rights icon Medgar Evers in Jackson, Mississippi — at the very house where he was assassinated. This was one of the most meaningful/emotional interviews I've had the privilege to photograph. Powerful article by @deneen_washpost, and big thanks to editor @markumpixs. Link in profile.
Reflecting on island time that left a permanent imprint — Jamaica 🇯🇲

New work for @de_volkskrant (Amsterdam) alongside writer @thomasrueb. We traveled to Florida to report on record-breaking heat and ocean temperatures. We linked up with a coral reef restoration program trying to revitalize coral populations in the Florida Keys. Time will tell, but these unprecedented temperatures could devastate the reefs. One diver said the water was so hot, even 30 feet below the surface, it felt like he was sweating underwater.

This one for the @nytimes was another tough assignment. "Where the Sheriff Is King, These Women Say He Coerced Them Into Sex" in rural Mississippi — stellar investigative reporting by @ilyssadaly + @jmitchellnews. Big thanks to editor stephenreiss. Link in bio.
Ms. Gail, so much joy for over 30 years at Doe's Eat Place — Greenville, MS

Latest work for @washingpost about the traumatic risks families are taking after Mississippi suddenly banned hormones and other gender-transition treatments for minors. Stellar reporting from @caseyparkswrites as we followed Ray, 17, and his mother Katie, on their journey across state lines to fulfill a prescription. Big thanks to editor @markumpixs. Link in bio.

Recent work for @waltonfamilyfdn about @theKKACorganization, a nonprofit based in the Delta, that is helping Black landowners and farmers regain control of their land after decades of discriminatory practices. KKAC also makes a big push for conservation, encouraging landowners to restore natural habits. Big thanks to co-founder Wilbur Peer and Sheldon Alberts. Link in bio.

Proud to be part of this global project from @Volksrkant (Amsterdam), featuring photographers from around the world photographing summer at night. The one rule was that photos had to be made from midnight to 6 a.m. All these years living in the Mississippi Delta, I've made countless trips out to the Mississippi River (always stopping along the way) to hike the banks with my camera, but I never did this after midnight. All senses were heightened and it was a lot of fun photographing in the Delta darkness. Pretty cool when a raccoon fishing on the banks of the river walked right into my long exposure. Big thanks to @veroniquesmedts + @thomasrueb
Leroy and his Black Diamond watermelon — Cleveland, MS

Another devastating investigation assignment for the @nytimes + @mstodaynews about the Rankin County Sheriff's Department. When Damien Cameron, 29, died in August 2021, it was clear that he fell victim to police brutality. Monica Lee, Cameron's mother, maintains that deputies violently subdued him and ignored his cries that he couldn't breathe. Link in profile.

@washingtonpost sent me out to photograph the extreme heat in Mississippi this summer, so I got up before sunrise to capture Delta State's voluntary football workouts. Also got some Cleveland Central High School marching band pics that didn't make the cut. There's no way to avoid the sweat down here in the summer! Nice to share the space online with a group of talented photographers. Big thanks to editor @maxlbecherer. Link in bio.

Adventurous assignment for @Volksrkant (from Amsterdam) hunting for invasive pythons in the Florida Everglades. Writer @tomasrueb and I documented hunter Donna Kalil, 61, who has almost 800 python catches in her career. I'm not a fan of snakes, so this one really tested my bravery. Last photo by Rueb. Big thanks editor @veroniquesmedts

New work for @outdoor_life about old-school trotline fishing along a pristine section of the White River in rural Arkansas. Trotlines consist of a weighted rope with evenly spaced baited hooks that catch fish after the line is set — one of the South's most traditional fishing methods. Great reporting from @krebfish and big thanks to the Heavner family for showing us their beautiful stretch of wilderness. Link in bio.

Incredible! @lenapizzabagels + @marisoldo featured in the brand new issue of @GardenAndGun, with eloquent writing from @johntedge. Thank you so much for shining some light on Marisol's efforts to make the tastiest pizza and bagels — she shapes each and every one one by hand, and has a great team around her making it all possible. We've been open for about 6 months and couldn't be more grateful for all the support 🍕🔥🥯

It’s been an incredible ride these first few months at @lenapizzabagels along with a lot of unexpected media coverage! @marisoldo and her team are killing it. What an honor to have @fujifilmx_us come by and produce a short film about me documenting Marisol on their stellar X-H2S camera. Pretty advanced technology built into the camera so I can send photos to editors directly from the camera! Big thanks Fujifilm + @varina_hart 🙏 Watch the film at link in bio.
Honored to make the cover shots for the current issues of these Mississippi staples — @deltamagazine + @mississippimagazine

Work for @nytimes about the brutal heat this summer across the nation. I spent some time with USDA bee researchers in Stoneville, Miss. who had to restrict their fieldwork to early mornings due to high temps. Big thanks to editor @heather_casey

Adventurous assignment for @BitterSoutherner alongside writer @boyceu about chefs from New Orleans exploring the marshes and estuaries that make the city a culinary marvel. Truly fascinating to explore some hard-to-reach landscape. Big thanks to the BS team. Link in bio.
George Ray Hughes, 84 • Vietnam vet — Greenville, MS
Blessed for this assignment — 🍁 Mother Nature

Doesn't get much better than photographing @marisoldo for a cover shot! In less than 6 months, she's racked up a ton of media coverage for @lenapizzabagels (please follow). I'm incredibly proud to see her recognized for her hard work and dedication. Huge thanks to @PMQMagazine, the leading pizza mag in the industry. Link in bio 🍕

I'm incredibly honored to be included in @TIME’s Top 100 Photos of 2023 — but this photo is a reminder that Jackson, Mississippi's water issues have not been fully resolved, even if the topic hasn't been front page news recently. An outdated and frail water system leaves most Jackson residents unable to drink their tap water. Shot on assignment for @Guardian. Big thanks to @kimbubello + @sangsuk.jpg. See the very powerful Top 100 from my peers at the link in profile.

It's hard to post news of brutality in Mississippi, but it's necessary. New work out today for @NyTimes and @MSTodayNews about Rankin County "Goon Squad" sheriff deputies roaming impoverished neighborhoods and beating, tasing, abusing and assaulting residents. Please read the phenomenal reporting from @jerrymitchellnews, @steelandballast + @n.r.o.s.e.n.f.i.e.l.d, and big thanks to editor stephenreiss. Link in profile.

This image of mine was included in @CNN's 2023: The Year in Pictures — and it's a tragic reminder of the devastating EF4 tornado that ripped through Rolling Fork, Mississippi on March 24, 2023. Chuck's Dairy Bar was completely demolished. Owner Tracy Harden saved lives that night by rushing folks into the walk-in cooler just before the storm hit. If you've been to Rolling Fork recently, you've seen a lot of rebuilding going on, and Chuck's...its walls are up and the re-opening is near. Photographed on assignment for @nytimes. Big thanks to editor @bptuazon 🙏 View the entire list at link in profile.

New work out today for the @Guardian. Sisters Joann Murray (left) and Sandy Hays sit for a portrait at their church in Shreveport, Louisiana. Their brother died from heat stroke this summer. Louisiana’s Mike Johnson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, is a denier of climate science — even when his constituents have faced extreme heat, drought and a record number of heat-related deaths. Great reporting from @ollyla, and huge thanks to editor @fletchinator. Link in profile.

New work out today for @nytimes about a major problem in our nation’s food chain — draining our limited groundwater resources to feed the animals we eventually eat. I drove across Arkansas, Tennessee and Mississippi, focussing on our increase in chicken consumption. Amazing reporting @sominisengupta and big thanks to editor @mcmarbled. Link in bio.

More difficult investigation work for @nytimes + @mstodaynews. Numerous allegations of jailhouse rape, brutal beatings, and corrupt acts by sheriffs and their deputies have been ignored or disregarded across Mississippi. The question lingers — who investigates the sheriff? Incredibly powerful reporting by @ilyssadaly + @jmitchellnews. Big thanks to editor stephenreiss. Link in bio.
RIP Red Paden, a juke joint legend — Clarksdale, MS

So cool to kick off 2024 with the cover shot for the brand new @VisitMS tourism guide. When we moved to MS, I was a young photographer, and I was immediately struck by the design of this annual guide. You can find it all over the state at visitor/welcome centers. Always thought it would be awesome to photograph the cover. Pulled this off with my drone too!
Esteban, the calabaza farmer — Esperanza, Sonora, México 🇲🇽

Coverage of a big winter storm in Mississippi for the @nytimes National desk today. We’ve had a number of ice/snow storms in recent years, but something really caught my attention today — Cleveland, MS doesn’t have an emergency shelter if the power grid goes down. Eerily reminds me of a few years back when Texans died from the extreme cold down here in the South. Homeless folks and people without a backup power source at home are literally left out in the cold. Big thanks to editors @heather_casey @jennifermosbrucker + stephenreiss
